\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb360\sa200\li0\ri0\f1\fs48\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 System Styles\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Calliope supports named system styles. A system style determines the specific properties of a system, including number of staves, number of lines, various formatting options, size, part name, \i etc\i0 . Any change made to a system style is reflected in all systems using that style, making it easier to achieve a consistent document appearance.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Every system in a document can have a style associated with it. The known styles are listed in the System Styles panel of the System Inspector, and it is possible to create new styles, modify existing styles, and and delete styles..  By default, no style is assigned to a system. \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The System Styles panel has a browser listing the known styles, a textfield, and six buttons.  The style of the current system is highlighted.  The following example shows several styles as used in an opera score: \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_2.tiff \width4960\height3440
